# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hitachi-rail-sts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] A train approaching a section is *offered* by a signalman to his counterpart at the next signal box.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] If the section is clear, the latter *accepts* the train, and the first signalman may clear his signals to give permission for the train to enter the section.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] This communication traditionally takes place by bell codes and status indications transmitted over a simple telegraph wire circuit between signalmen using a device called a *block instrument*, although some contemporary block working is operated wirelessly.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] This process is repeated for every block section a train passes through.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The absolute block system does not replace the use of any other form of signalling, such as fixed signals, hand signals, or detonators – and, in fact, usually relies on fixed signals.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] This was sometimes insufficient to prevent a train colliding with the rear of one that had stopped unexpectedly.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] In absolute block working, a *block section* (or simply *section*) is a section of railway line between one signal box and another.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The signal box towards which a train travels is said to be *in advance* and the signal box from which it travels is said to be *in rear*.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] A block section is normally the section of track from the most advanced signal controlled by the signal box in rear, and the rearmost signal controlled by the signal box in advance.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Because many signal boxes are at stations, the last signal controlled by the rear box is called the *starter signal*, whether or not there is a station at which trains stop.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] This signal, and the rearmost signal controlled by the box ahead, are *stop signals*, which a train should not pass if they are in the on position, showing a red light.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The first stop signal controlled by a box is called the *home signal*.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] A *distant signal* is also provided some distance from the home signal, which will only show a *clear* aspect if all stop signals under a signal box's control are clear, and will otherwise show *caution* – this gives a driver advance warning of a need to stop.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Some signal boxes have an *intermediate block section*, or *IBS*.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] This normally takes the place of an old absolute block section, and is commonly found where former absolute block sections and their associated signal boxes have been removed.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Essentially an intermediate block section allows two block sections, and therefore two trains, to be on the same line but controlled by the same signal box.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Typically, a signal box with an intermediate block section will have a home signal (and associated distant signal), starting signal and an intermediate block home signal which has its own distant signal.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The line from the starting signal to the intermediate block home signal is called the intermediate block home section.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The line from the intermediate block home signal to the home signal of the next signal box on the same line in the same direction of travel is the absolute block section.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] To clear the intermediate block home signal a "line clear" is required from the signal box in advance.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] An intermediate block section means that a train can approach the intermediate block home signal while there is a train between the intermediate block home signal and the home signal of the next signal box on the same line in the same direction of travel.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Generally, all intermediate block home signals and their respective distants are colour light signals, normally showing two aspects.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The extent of the line from the rearmost home signal to the most advanced starting signal controlled from the same signal box is called *station limits* at that signal box (this does not necessarily refer to a passenger station).
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Within station limits, the signalman controls the safe movement, and in normal circumstances he can directly see the position of trains there.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Usually no communication with other signalmen is needed for movements within station limits.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Electrical telegraphy was the first practical use of current electricity and was developed in the 1840s and 1850s at the same time as the development of railways.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The first commercial electrical telegraph was the Cooke and Wheatstone system.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] In July 1837 William Fothergill Cooke installed a demonstration system on the Euston to Camden Town section of Robert Stephenson's London and Birmingham Railway for signalling rope-hauling of carriages (as the locomotives could not cope with the steep incline).
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Cooke also put forward the idea of dividing a single line into *grand divisions* of between 15 and 20 miles (24 and 32 km), each subdivided into *stages* 2 to 5 miles (3.2 to 8.0 km) long that were to be connected together by telegraph, with instruments that showed the state of each stage.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] In 1842 he published these ideas in a book entitled *Telegraphic Railways: Or the Single Way Recommended by Safety, Economy, and Efficiency, Under the Safeguard and Control of the Electric Telegraph*.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Cooke's ideas were not taken up by the railway companies until the 1850s and 1860s.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] When they were developed into a practical system, it provided the ability for signalmen to communicate with each other and provided the basis for the absolute block system.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] By 1872 it was used on 44% of lines in Britain, rising to 75% by the end of the decade and was made mandatory on passenger-carrying lines in 1889.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] It successfully managed train control over most of the British railway system until generally superseded by more sophisticated systems from 1950.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] British Railways standard block instrument.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] At the bottom is the tapper, bell and the commutator switch that is used to set the status of the block (close-up on the right).
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Above that is the indicator of the block's status which is also seen in an adjacent signal box.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] At the top is a repeater display of the status of the adjacent block.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Block instruments are located in signal boxes.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Originally the different displays and commutator handle were in a variety of cabinets.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The standard British Railways block instrument brought them together in a single small cabinet; its front face displaying two indicators, a commutator handle, a bell and a tapper.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The upper indicator shows the state of the forward block – along the line leading away from the signal box.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The commutator is used by the signalman to indicate the state of his block, and the lower indicator displays this state, which is also displayed on a repeater indicator in the box for the block from which a train will come.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] At the bottom is a single-stroke bell and the tapper to sound the bell in the next box.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The commutator and each of the two indicators has three positions: normal (or line blocked), line clear, and train on line.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] In the simplest case of a signal box serving a two-track section, there will be two block instruments, one for communicating with each of the neighbouring boxes.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The **signalling bell**, also known as a **block bell**, is used in conjunction with the block instruments if the bell is not integrated with them.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Each bell has its own distinctive sound so that the signalman knows which box is communicating with him.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Each communication starts with a single strike of the bell meaning "Call attention".
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The recipient signalman then shows that he has received the message by repeating it back to the sender.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] All subsequent bell messages are acknowledged promptly by repeating back to the sender – with the single exception of six strikes which indicate "Obstruction danger" which is not echoed back until all relevant signals have been set to "Stop".
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] An example is the process of signalling a train in the up direction (from A to C) past a signal box B.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The signal box in rear is A and the signal box in advance is C.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The block indicators at B are in the Normal position.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] If the signalman at B can accept the train safely (if the line is clear up to B's clearing point and will not need to be blocked by another train) he "accepts" the train by repeating the bell signal, and placing the commutator on his block instrument for the section from A to "Line Clear".
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The "Line Clear" is repeated at box A, and allows the signalman at A to clear, or "pull off", his signals.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] In case the line is not clear, B simply does not acknowledge A's "Is Line Clear?", and leaves the commutator in the Normal position.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] At this point, B will not clear any of his signals.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Firstly, he cannot clear his starting signal without a "Line Clear" from C.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Finally, his distant will not clear without both his home and starting signals being clear.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] As the train passes the starting signal at A, the signalman there sends the "Train Entering Section" signal (2 beats) on the block bell to B, and the signalman at B acknowledges the signal and moves the commutator to "Train On Line".
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] His lower indicator on the block indicator to A repeats the position of the commutator.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] B may now clear his signals for the train.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] After an interval, the train will arrive and pass B; as it does so, B sends "Train Entering Section" on the block bell to C.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Then C acknowledges the bell signal and places the block instrument to "Train On Line".
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] As the train passes, he restores his signals to danger, and when the whole of the train passes B complete with tail lamp attached, B sends the "Train Out Of Section" bell signal (2-1) to A and when A acknowledges it, he places his block indicator to "Normal".
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The block section between A and B is now normal and A can offer B another train, if he has one.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] When the train has reached C, the signalman there sends "Train Out Of Section" on the block bell and when B acknowledges it, C places the block indicator to "Normal".
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Bell codes are used to communicate with adjacent signal boxes.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] They can communicate information regarding the type of train being offered, the status of trains within sections or emergency information.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] A bell code is acknowledged as being understood by repetition.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Nearly all bell codes are preceded by a single stroke on the bell, referred to as *Call Attention* — the main exception being *Train Entering Section*.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] The *Is Line Clear?* bell signal describes the train, distinguishing between ordinary and express passenger trains, and various categories of goods train.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] In some locations, routing information is included in the bell code, such an ordinary passenger train to be routed to a branch at the signal box in advance would be offered by the bell code 1-3 instead of 3-1.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] All trains, whether operated by a (passenger) train operating company (TOC) or a freight operating company (FOC), are allocated to one of ten classes, as set out below.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] It is a generalised guide intended to assist signalling staff in prioritising trains according to their importance as well as ensuring that any special instructions that may apply at a specific location are carried out.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Passenger trains are generally classified in accordance with their stopping pattern while the classification of freight trains depends upon maximum permitted speeds.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/absolute-block-signalling] Class 1 trains (together with Class 9 services, which are officially their equivalent in this regard) have the highest priority, followed by Class 2 and then so on down the list.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Adtranz manufactured locomotives, high-speed, regional, metro and underground passenger trains, trams and people movers as well as freight wagons.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Non-rolling stock businesses included railway electrification and signalling infrastructure.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] On 8 May 1995, ABB and Daimler-Benz proposed a merger of their rail industry-related activities into a single autonomous 50:50 joint venture; the combined group would be the largest rail-technology company in the world.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] In Germany the combined company, along with Siemens would have a duopoly or near-duopoly in the market areas of electric locomotives, mainline and regional electric and diesel multiple units, trams and metros, and catenary systems.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] In the EU, outside Germany, the merger would have meant no significant market share increase, including Scandinavia, where ABB had a dominant market share.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The proposed merger was approved by government regulators on 18 October 1995, on the condition that both companies divest themselves of any shares in Kiepe, a traction components company.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The merger came into force on 1 January 1996.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The company's manufacturing facilities and product lines were rationalised, including a standard form of car body; after 18 months manufacturing costs had been reduced by 30%, revenues and orders also rose from 1996 to 1997.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] However the company continued to lose money, $111 million in 1997.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Polish manufacturer Pafawag was acquired in 1997 and the facility modernised, controlling interests in *MÁV Dunakeszi*, Hungary and *Schindler Waggon* Switzerland were also acquired by the end of 1997.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] A new diesel locomotive design with engine and electrical traction system provided by General Electric was introduced, named "Blue Tiger".
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Adtranz intended to consolidate its product range around these families once on-going deliveries were finished.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Adtranz continued operating at a loss in 1998, attributed to earlier contracts with underestimated costs, as well as technical problems with products, in spite of an order for 400 locomotives from Deutsche Bahn, necessitating the acquisition of Swiss Locomotive and Machine Works.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] In January 1999, ABB sold its 50% stake in Adtranz to DaimlerChrysler for $472 million, taking up a previous agreement made on the formation of the joint venture whereby DaimlerChrysler was required to purchase ABB's stake.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Adtranz finally achieved profitability in 2000, as DaimlerChrysler prepared to sell off Adtranz.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The Greenbrier Companies acquired the freight wagon manufacturing business in January 2000.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The overhead electrification systems installations business was sold to Balfour Beatty in late 2000 for €153 million.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] No buyer was found for the railway signalling division.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The remaining assets of Adtranz were sold to Bombardier, in a $711 million deal announced in August 2000, a price considered to be low by industry analysts.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The sale was cleared by the European Union in April 2001 on the condition that Bombardier would license or sell the Adtranz regional train and tram products to Stadler Rail in the German market, due to the large market share of Bombardier and Adtranz in the country.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The deal would make Stadler a viable independent company providing competition to Bombardier.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The takeover came into legal effect on 1 May 2001 with a final price of $725 million and ADtranz was folded into the Bombardier Transportation division.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Within months of the sale, Bombardier said that it was misled about the financial situation of Adtranz.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Bombardier sued DaimlerChrysler for providing misleading financial information.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The companies settled in September 2004 with DaimlerChrysler agreeing to refund $209 million, making the final sale price for Adtranz just $516 million.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The brand *Adtranz* was created by Landor Associates as part of the corporate identity of ***A**BB **D**aimler Ben**z** **Tran**sportation*.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] It is an acronym derived from selected letters of the complete name of the first company using it: *A*BB *D*aimler-Benz *Trans*portation, with a *z* in place of an *s* at the end for the name to imply a complete product platform from A to Z.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] It was capitalised by the companies with a capital *D* as *ADtranz*, following the standard English text formatting and capitalisation rules it is spelled with a small *d* as *Adtranz*.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Above the text *ADtranz*, the company logo included a green dot, symbolising a signal set on green, as well as the environmental friendliness of railways.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] The company also registered the slogan *ADtranz – we speak railways*.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/adtranz] Rights on the brand and slogan were deleted in 2008 and 2007 respectively.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] ACSES provides railway trains with positive enforcement of "civil" speed restrictions (those based on the physical characteristics of the line).
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The on-board components keep track of a train's position and continuously calculates a maximum safe braking curve for upcoming speed restrictions.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] If the train exceeds the safe braking curve then the brakes are automatically applied.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Data regarding permanent speed restrictions and other information about the permanent way and track configuration is obtained in chunks from the track mounted transponders and stored in an onboard database.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Information regarding temporary speed restrictions is given to the train while en route via a wireless data system.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The on-board equipment tracks the train's position by counting wheel rotations between the transponders, which also serve as fixed location references.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] In the event a train's crew exceeds a speed restriction a penalty brake application is applied bringing the train to a complete stop in the same fashion as existing automatic train control (ATC) systems.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Speed restrictions required by the signal system are provided by the legacy Pulse code cab signaling system, which has been in service on various railroads since the 1930s.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The cab signal codes are fed into the ACSES cab display unit, which then enforces the more restrictive of the two speeds.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The on-board ACSES unit is backward compatible and can function where only the cab signaling is present without the ACSES overlay as well of situations where ACSES is available without cab signals.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] ACSES also enforces a positive stop at signals displaying an absolute Stop indication.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The transponder information allows the train to keep track of when it is approaching an absolute signal and then determine if a positive stop is required depending on cab signal indication and information provided via a local data radio.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The system is calibrated to stop the train somewhere within the "Positive Stop Zone", which extends up to 1000 feet from the absolute stop signal itself.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] To pass the stop signal or otherwise move the train in absence of a more favorable signal indication a *Stop Release* button must be engaged by the engineer before the brakes can be released.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Due to several limitations of the ACSES system and various contingency operations, employees must still be familiar with all permanent and temporary speed restrictions.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] ACSES is meant to supplement rather than replace employees' knowledge and skills.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The combination of continuous cab signals and ACSES meet the definition of a positive train control (PTC) system by providing collision protection, enforcement of all speed restrictions and enforcement of track possession by maintenance forces.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The on-board equipment consists of a computer that also stores the route characteristics database, a distance measurement subsystem to track train position, an antenna subsystem for the track mounted balises, and a data radio subsystem for communication with wayside systems.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] In the cab, the driver has a consolidated display which displays the train's ACSES target speed along with the cab signal speed and other useful operating information.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Messages conveyed to and from locomotive and ground-based systems are made up of Advanced Train Control System (ATCS) encoded message frames.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The system begins with passive transponders attached between the tracks which are electrically powered by an electromagnetic field when a locomotive passes over them.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The transponders digitally convey their identification information and other relevant bits of information wirelessly via an onboard antenna, allowing the locomotives to know precisely when they have reached a particular waypoint.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] This location information is utilized by the on-board systems when consulting its database of speed restrictions and track characteristics to calculate a real time braking curve.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Wayside Communications Managers (WCM) (or packet switches) link all the BCMs in the region to a backhaul network which allows them to communicate with the dispatcher's office and associated control systems via TCP/IP.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] This design provides locomotives with information about speed restrictions as soon as they go into effect without having to rely on voice communications with the train crew.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Additional BCMs (data radios) located at interlockings transmit information relating to absolute Stop signal indications and any speed restrictions pertaining to the train's route through said interlocking.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Speed information acquired in this fashion will be displayed on the ACSES speed readout to supplement any speed information provided by the cab signaling system.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] After a positive stop the data radios will also transmit information releasing the train from the stop when track conditions permit.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Such information about the status of the track occupancy, switch position, signal indication, and a host of other vital inputs—is accumulated by wayside encoders, such as a Safetran VIU-ACSES (see photo to the right), before being sent to the BCMs for transmission to locomotives.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The ACSES system also supports the use of temporary fixed transponders to enforce temporary speed restrictions as an alternative or backup to using the wireless network.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] One transponder is placed a safe braking distance from the start of the restriction to engage it, and a second is placed at the end to release it.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] In the office where dispatch and control is performed, a system provides a visual indication of the current status of communications with all locomotives as well as a close approximation of where each locomotive is currently located along the track.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] In the event that maintenance is needed along any section of the track, before a work crew is dispatched or before a work crew is granted authority to proceed, a temporary speed restriction (TSR) is created in the office computer systems.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] After a series of verifications and procedures, the TSR is presented to the ACSES office system.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] When a locomotive issues a query for TSRs for a given region, the WCM conveys the request for information to the office system via TCP/IP and the response is conveyed back to the locomotive which updates its local database with any restrictions.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] There are a number of redundant components in the overall ACSES system such that a failure of a subsystem will swap over to another automatically.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The loss of a WCM, for example, due to a power outage or lightning strike results in a standby WCM taking over the communications duties between BCMs and the office systems.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Because a locomotive's radio is capable of being heard by a number of BCMs, the WCM examines the indication RF signal strength of each BCM that heard the locomotive to determine what the strongest talk path back to the locomotive is.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] The WCM maintains a record of three possible talk paths to the locomotive such that the strongest path is always selected if the office needs to communicate back to the locomotive.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] As a locomotive moves from region to region, the radio signal strengths are recorded by BCMs which get conveyed to the WCMs change.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] BCMs which fall out of range of locomotives are removed from talk path routes within the WCM in favor of the BCMs which are coming into range.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] In this way the WCM is constantly aware of where each locomotive is located and which talk path is best used to communicate with the locomotive.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Such information is also conveyed to the office so that office systems may make use of it.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Finally, the cab signals are considered a completely independent system that transmits a continuous stream of codes through the rails instead of via wireless transmission.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Any fault in the ACSES overlay will not affect the cab signal system and moreover a cab signal failure will not affect the ACSES system.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] If a locomotive is unable to automatically retrieve temporary speed restriction information, permanent speed restrictions will continue to be enforced.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] In the event of a total failure of the on-board ACSES system the engineer may revert to the use of the cab signal system without civil speed enforcement.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] Both situations require permission to be obtained from the train dispatcher and are accompanied by additional maximum speed restrictions.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] At interlockings where the Data Radio (BCM) is either not installed or not functioning, the train will determine if a positive stop is necessary via the cab signaling system.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-civil-speed-enforcement-system] If it is necessary to pass a signal at Stop after receiving authorization from the dispatcher, ACSES will limit the train to 15 miles per hour (24 km/h) within the interlocking limits after use of the Stop Release button.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The **Advanced Train Management System** is a train control system under development by Lockheed Martin for the Australian Rail Track Corporation (ARTC).
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] ATMS uses Global Positioning System to locate and track the position of trains within the ARTC network.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] ATMS has been proposed as a low cost functional equivalent to European Rail Traffic Management System.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The technology was originally intended for use across the Nullarbor Plain to connect the eastern states of Australia with Perth and Western Australia.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] However, after 20 years of delays, it was announced that Trans-Australian Railway would instead be equipped with Train Management and Control System (TMACS).
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] ATMS is a rail safe working system based on radio communication.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] Authorities are issued to equipped trains to allow them to proceed to a specified point.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The ATMS compares the movement of an equipped train to the authority which has been issued, and then brakes the train if it exceeds the authority.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] ATMS does not use balises, such as the ETCS system from Europe.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] ATMS's particular strength is to improve safety and efficiency in remote areas where communications and power infrastructure is limited, such as in deserts.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] It thus involves a mixture of land-based and satellite technologies for communications and renewable power supplies due to lack of mains electricity in many cases.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] Excellent following headways on single lines is provided, in excess of what is economically possible with conventional intermediate block signals.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The cost of level crossing protection is reduced due to the elimination of the need for track circuits.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] Trains speeds are regulated according to the speeds along the track and through turnouts (switches).
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] After 13 years of development, ATMS was implemented on the short Port Augusta to Whyalla railway.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The next phase is between Port Augusta via Adelaide to Melbourne.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The Inland Railway is to benefit from a $20m contract for its 1700 km of track.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] Drivers use a touch screen device located in the console – called a Driver Machine Interface or DMI – which provides information on the train’s movement and integrity, authority, target speed location, as well as other traffic, geographic and track features.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The DMI enhances a driver’s situational awareness through a 10 km ‘look ahead’ view of work sites and changes in network conditions.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] A blue column bar represents the train’s length, direction of travel as well as the kilometre post position.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The lower green horizontal line represents the train’s movement authority.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] Once a train has an authority, it can continue to the limit of its authority autonomously even if communications fail.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] Before moving into ATMS territory, the train communicates with the Network Control Centre (NCC) and the driver enters data via the DMI - digitally connecting the driver, train and NCC in real time.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] Train crews are automatically advised of speed restrictions, approaching speed limit changes as well as track work locations.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] When a train is within 10 km of a temporary speed restriction, a yellow braking curve followed by an alert will appear on the DMI.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The Location Determination System (LDS) software uses a highly sophisticated dual feed from two GPS antennas to fix the train’s location.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The software compares these two GPS inputs then further compares onboard sensors, the tachometer, and the track database to exactly fix the train’s location.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] Under normal conditions, location reporting to ATMS occurs every 15 seconds.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] The Train Control & Display (TC&D) software controls train functions such as train integrity monitoring, braking enforcement, driver display management and message exchange between the DMI and AMS.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/advanced-train-management-system] Because of delays in the development of ATMS, it was decided to equip the Port Augusta - Tarcoola section with conventional CTC signalling.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Thomson acquired magazine publisher Faulkner & Gray in 1992.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Thomson Financial expanded significantly when it acquired **Primark**, another financial information provider, on June 6, 2000, for $842 million in an all-cash deal.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Primark owned many brands in both the U.S. and UK/Europe such as Datastream, Baseline Financial, Intellivate Capital Ventures (ICV), and IBES.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] The acquisition consolidated and combined competing financial information provision, for example the FirstCall and IBES earnings estimate data, under the same company.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Thomson Financial sold its Thomson Media division in 2004.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] On 17 April 2008, the Thomson Corporation merged with Reuters and created the new company Thomson Reuters.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Thomson Financial and Reuters combined their businesses into the Markets Division: Sales & Trading, Enterprise, Investment & Advisory, and Media.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] The other Thomson operations were combined into the Professional Division: Legal, Healthcare & Science, and Tax & Accounting.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Thomson Reuters Financial & Risk eventually became Refinitiv.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Thomson Financial had many offices across the US, Europe, and Asia Pacific regions.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] The head office was based in Boston (1987-2008) and New York (joint with Boston), with significant presence in San Francisco, London, Frankfurt, Bangalore, Manila, and many satellite offices in locations such as Sydney, Hong Kong, Tokyo, Zurich, Geneva, just as some examples.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] The two major data centers, not including smaller points of presence, for Thomson Financial were located in NYC and New Jersey.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] In June 2007, Thomson Financial agreed to buy seven Asia-Pacific news bureaus from Xinhua Finance.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] The bureaus purchased were in Tokyo, Manila, Jakarta, Kuala Lumpur, Singapore, Sydney and Seoul.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Xinhua Finance stated they would retain their operations in Beijing, Shanghai, Hong Kong and Taipei.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] The company had a wide variety of financial products.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] **Thomson ONE** is a core product, although legacy branded offerings such as *Datastream Advance* and *Global Topic* will probably remain for a few years.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Thomson ONE was a competitor of Bloomberg L.P., Capital IQ and FactSet Research Systems.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] There were different packages of Thomson ONE, i.e., Thomson ONE for Investment Management, Thomson ONE for Investment Banking, etc.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/afx-news] Due to the acquisition of Primark and buyout of ILX Systems, Thomson Financial had seen growth over the previous four years and had seen improvement in the core product Thomson ONE.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] The name ALSN (АЛСН - автоматическая локомотивная сигнализация непрерывного действия) is composed of ALS, literally "Automatic Locomotive Signalling" (АЛС - автоматическая локомотивная сигнализация) and the variant designation N "Continuous Effect" (Н - Непрерывного действия).
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] Other variants are built according to the same scheme like ALST (АЛСТ) for "Fixed Point Automatic Train Signalling" (АЛС точечного действия) and ALSR (АЛСР) for "Radio-Based Automatic Train Signalling" (АЛС с использованием радиоканала).
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] The term ALS-ARS (АЛС-АРС) refers to "Automatic Train Signalling with Automatic Speed Regulation" (автоматическая локомотивная сигнализация с автоматическим регулированием скорости) used in subways which is a form of an automatic train control system.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] The system makes use of several distinct pulse train patterns of alternating current flowing through a track circuit to convey an aspect of the next signal.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] The circuit comprises the feedpoint at the next signal, one running rail, first locomotive axle, another running rail and back to the signal feedpoint.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] The resulting electromagnetic field is picked up by receiver coils located just front of the first axle of the locomotive.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] The signal is then amplified, filtered and evaluated.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] The benefits of the system are relative encoder simplicity (a simple motor-operated camwheel closing and opening relay contacts generates the pulse train) and the ability to use the same signal for track occupancy detection.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] The drawbacks are a somewhat long response time unsuitable for high speed operation (which resulted in ALS-EN's implementation), and the necessity to switch between 25/50/75 Hz frequency variants depending on traction current type (AC/DC) and other conditions.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] A new, modular ALSN automatic train protection onboard system VEPS has been under development since 2002 in Estonia.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] Based on programmable logic controller technologies, the system was developed by Estonian Railway engineers and patented in 2004 by Indrek Syld.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] The new system was installed in the CE35 type of locomotive (77 systems) during 2003–2004.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] A new platform (level 2.0) was installed on Stadler's FLIRT trains for Estonia in 2012 (76 systems), and in 2016 a third generation of the system was introduced for the international market.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] Since the 1990s, the Russian Railroad Company has introduced a computerized successor system KLUB-U which requires either ALSN only or both, ALSN and ALS-EN sensors for compatibility.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] In ERTMS the ALSN/ALS-EN systems are listed as ETCS Class-B systems.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] A similar in general theory of operation, but differently implemented, is an ALS-ARS system used in subways of the former Soviet Union.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] It uses low frequency signals transmitted and received as described above, with the difference that the signals are continuous wave and the signal's *frequency* determines its code meaning, which results in much faster response time.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] Typically, two frequencies are transmitted at the same time, indicating the current speed limit and, if lower, the limit for the next section, providing the train driver with a warning and time to react and reduce speed.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] In case of an overspeed, the train is unconditionally braked to the indicated speed limit, and then, if not acknowledged by a driver pressing a vigilance button, to a complete stop.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/alsn] Should be there no frequency received (such as on an uncoded track in a maintenance depot or in case of an equipment failure), the driver may proceed at a low speed while holding a vigilance pedal.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] Communication between the train and the trackside equipment happens entirely through bidirectional radio communication.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] Radio base stations are placed at intervals of 2 to 3 km and operates on four different frequency bands, used alternately to prevent inference.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] Radios operate in the 400 MHz frequency band, with data transmitted using TDMA access method with Reed–Solomon error correction at 9.6 kbps.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] The radio system are based on proprietary standards with encryption.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] The ground controller, being the main control unit of ground equipment, is responsible for the identification of train locations based on information received from the trains, route setting, control and interlocking, train interval regulation, and boundary control and train entry/exit handover.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] Connected to the ground controller, the train existence supervision equipment is responsible for controlling line occupation of trains.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] It also maintains safety in case of system failure and during recovery operations by using train identification assigned to each trains to track occupation even if other equipment is out of service.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] The system supervision equipment monitors the operating status of the ATACS system and has functions to change settings such as temporary speed limits in increments of 5 km/h.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] The system supervision equipment is also responsible for setting track closures, setting single-line working, and routing maintenance vehicles.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] The field controller connects trackside equipment such as switches, level crossing equipment, radio stations, and detectors to the ground controller.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] Every train is equipped with an onboard device which is responsible for determining the train's position.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] For more precise position tracking, a balise is installed every kilometer.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] This information, along with the train length is periodically transferred to the ground equipment.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] Therefore, no track circuits or axle counters are necessary.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] The onboard device is also responsible for calculating the brake intervention curve required to stop the train at the limit of the limited movement authority (LMA), the area in which the train is permitted to move.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] It takes the individual train's braking performance, track gradient, curve, and speed limit into consideration to perform this calculation.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] Similar to earlier Automatic Train Control systems, ATACS uses cab signalling.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/atacs] A cab display shows ATACS information required for driving, such as the distance to limit of the LMA, the maximum allowable speed as permitted by the brake curve, and the route set.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Headquartered in Naples, Italy, it is a wholly owned subsidiary of Hitachi Rail.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] It was previously listed on the Borsa Italiana and was a component of the benchmark FTSE Italia Mid Cap Index.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Providing design, manufacture, installation, integration and maintenance of a wide range of train control systems and equipment, Hitachi Rail STS employs 4,574 people as of 2026.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] The company’s namesake comes from the Italian company Gio.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Ansaldo & C., which was founded in 1853 in Genoa, Italy by Giovanni Ansaldo.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Ansaldo & C.* began as a steam locomotive producer, which diversified into shipbuilding and electrical and nuclear energy production.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In 1881, the US company Union Switch & Signal (US&S) was founded by George Westinghouse in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania from the assets of the Interlocking Switch & Signal Company (interlocking controls) and the Union Electric Signal Company.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] The latter was founded by the American engineer and inventor William Robinson, the father of track circuit systems.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In 1988 US&S was acquired by Ansaldo STS, operating independently until 2009, when it became "Ansaldo STS USA", the North American subsidiary of Ansaldo.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In Europe, Ansaldo STS expanded acquiring the French company Compagnie des Signaux pour Chemins de fer (CSE) in 1996.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Founded in 1902 by Fernand Cumont with the support of the financial group Empain, CSE built the first lines of the Paris metro: the maintenance of these lines continues until today.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In 1920 CSE (independent since 1912) was renamed into Company and Business Electrical Signals (CSEE), concentrating on rail signaling and electrical manufacturing, contributing to create SAGEM and later (1996) entering in the Ansaldo Signal group.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In 1993 the parent company Ansaldo SpA was merged into the Finmeccanica holding, a state-owned entity privatized during the same year.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Ansaldo Segnalamento Ferroviario became the parent company of Ansaldo Signal (railway signalling), the owner of Union Switch & Signal and CSEE.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] The company was founded as "Ansaldo STS" in 2006 through the merger of Ansaldo Trasporti Sistemi Ferroviari and Ansaldo Signal.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] It began trading on the Milan Stock exchange, with 60% of its shares publicly held and 40% owned by Finmeccanica S.p.A.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Both companies had their roots in the Ansaldo engineering conglomerate which was gradually absorbed by Finmeccanica.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Ansaldo Trasporti Sistemi Ferroviari was created in 2000, acquiring certain units of Ansaldo Trasporti (which had been fully integrated into Finmeccanica) the following year.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] The creation of Ansaldo STS was followed by a partial IPO in March 2006.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] On 24 February 2015 Hitachi acquired Finmeccanica’s 51% shareholding and initiated a tender offer for the remaining shares of the company.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In the occasion of the Ordinary General Shareholders’ Meeting on 2 November, Hitachi Rail Italy Investment completed the acquisition of the 40% of the share capital of Ansaldo STS.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] During the first meeting of the new board of directors, chaired by Alistair Dormer, Stefano Siragusa was confirmed as chief executive officer and general manager of the company, with the powers to manage the company and the group.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In March 2015, after the public tender offer launch on the society and after the purchase of other shares at 10.5 euros each, Hitachi Rail Italy Investments arrived at 50.7% of the share capital.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Hitachi has a long term goal of integrating the company to provide a range of cars and signaling products and a manufacturing footprint in Europe.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Stefano Siragusa, chief executive officer and general manager of the company, resigned on 31 March 2016 and remained in charge until 13 May 2016 when, on the occasion of the shareholders’ general meeting the new board of directors were elected.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] On 24 May, the new Board appointed Andrew Barr as the new chief executive officer and general manager of Ansaldo STS.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Andrew Barr was also granted the operational powers necessary for the management of the company and the group.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In October 2018, Hitachi agreed to buy Elliot Management's remaining 32% shareholding.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Hitachi subsequently made a takeover offer for the remaining shares.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] On 22 January 2019 Hitachi announced it had gained a 99% shareholding.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Ansaldo STS was officially delisted from Borsa Italiana and renamed Hitachi Rail STS on 30 January 2019.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In 2024, Hitachi Rail and MERMEC signed a put option agreement for the sale of Hitachi Rail’s main line signalling business in France and its signalling business units in Germany and the UK.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] The company's operations are split into two divisions: Freight Rail and Passenger Railway / Mass Transit.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Major projects involving Hitachi Rail STS and its predecessor companies include the Copenhagen Metro, where it is responsible for the provision of rolling stock, Automatic Train Control, SCADA and other services; and signalling on LGV Est in France and High Speed 1 in the United Kingdom.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] The company also managed projects for signalling, train control and/or maintenance for the Metro systems of Paris, Los Angeles, Rome, Milan, Hong Kong, Naples, Shenyang, India, and Thessaloniki.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Hitachi Rail STS commissioned the first high-speed rail signaling system (TVM) for the first LGV line in France, in 1981, connecting Paris and Lyon.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In 2005, Hitachi Rail STS set another landmark with the first high speed line running on ERTMS Level 2 (European Rail Traffic Management System) between Rome and Naples, Italy.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] As of 2013 over half of all high speed lines worldwide (excluding Japan) are equipped with Hitachi Rail STS signaling.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In Europe, the company played a key role in the development and upgrade of ERTMS (level 1 and 2), leading to the interoperability of different countries' rail networks.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] In the United States Hitachi Rail STS has supported the freight rail industry, dating back over 130 years.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Hitachi Rail STS has products and systems with every Class I railroad in North America.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] A continuous, two way radio-based communication between wayside and carborne controllers used to determine train position and enforce movement authorities.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] The communication between adjacent zones, interlockings and carborne controllers supports safe optimized headways and maximizes system capacity.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] systems to the major urban centers across the United States, Europe and other countries.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Computer Aided Dispatching (CAD) system was developed by Union Switch & Signal at the Union Railroad Company in Duquesne, Pennsylvania, in 1966 starting the computer-aided dispatching in the industry.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Today Hitachi Rail STS adopts the Optimizing Traffic Planner as a late successor of the 1966 CAD.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] OTP is an advanced planning engine that solves complex logistics problems under changing operating conditions to maximize capacity and increase average velocity.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Computational agents respond in real-time to updated CAD and field data, issuing new movement plans that account for current conditions and all operating rules and constraints.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Applied off-line, OTP can minimize inherent conflict within a new timetable before the timetable is used in service.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] Applied on-line, OTP can produce significant capacity gains across a large freight oriented network.
[src:hitachi-rail-sts/hitachi-rail-sts] The company provides on-board and wayside components and systems, such as interlocking (MicroLok II), track circuits, switch machines (M-style), traditional and LED signals, Eurobalise, vital relays, hot wheel detectors, highway crossing mechanisms.
